The paper deals with the growth and structure of subspaces formed by the Schur product, which has applications in coding theory and cryptography. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Cryptography and Security (cs.CR), and Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper may also be relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category, as the Schur product has applications in network analysis. Finally, since the paper specifically focuses on constacyclic codes, it may also be relevant to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
